    overview:
      "## The core idea\n\nA traversal is a rule for the **order** in which you touch every node exactly once. The four classics split into two families. **Depth-first** dives down one branch before backtracking and comes in three flavors that differ only in *when you process the current node* relative to its children: **preorder** (node, left, right), **inorder** (left, node, right), **postorder** (left, right, node). **Breadth-first** (level order) sweeps the tree level by level using a queue.\n\n## How to think\n\nAsk one question: *when does the current node's work happen?* Preorder processes the root **before** descending, so it's natural for copying or serializing a tree top-down. Inorder on a **BST** yields values in **sorted order** — that single fact solves a huge class of problems. Postorder processes a node **after** both children, so it's the shape for any answer that depends on subtree results (heights, deletion, bottom-up DP). For anything keyed on *distance from the root* (shortest path in an unweighted tree, level sums, right-side view), reach for BFS.\n\n## Variants\n\n- **Recursive DFS** — three lines; the call stack does the bookkeeping.\n- **Iterative DFS** — an explicit stack; needed when recursion depth could blow the stack.\n- **Level order (BFS)** — a queue; snapshot `len(queue)` to separate levels.\n- **Morris traversal** — O(1) space by threading the tree, at the cost of temporarily mutating it.\n\n**Edge insight:** the empty tree (`root is None`) is the base case for every recursive traversal — handle it first and the rest falls out cleanly.",
