    overview:
      "## The core idea\n\nA **binary heap** is a complete binary tree (stored compactly in an array) obeying the **heap property**: every parent is <= its children (min-heap) or >= its children (max-heap). That single invariant makes the extreme element sit at the root, readable in **O(1)**, while insert and pop reshuffle along one root-to-leaf path in **O(log n)**. A **priority queue** is the abstract interface; a heap is its standard implementation.\n\n## How to think\n\nReach for a heap whenever you repeatedly need *the current best/worst element from a changing set* but never need the whole thing sorted. The litmus test is the phrase **'k-th largest', 'top k', 'most frequent', or 'merge sorted streams'**. The classic trick for **top-k**: keep a heap of size **k**. For the k largest, use a **min-heap of size k** — the root is the smallest of your current top-k, so anything smaller than it can be discarded in O(1). This gives **O(n log k)**, beating a full O(n log n) sort.\n\n## Variants\n\n- **Min-heap / max-heap** — Python's `heapq` is a min-heap; push negated values for a max-heap.\n- **Bounded top-k heap** — fixed size k, pop when it overflows.\n- **Two-heap (median)** — a max-heap for the low half, min-heap for the high half.\n- **Lazy-deletion heap** — mark stale entries and skip them on pop instead of removing in place.\n\n**Edge insight:** comparing tuples in a heap breaks if the second field isn't comparable — add a tie-breaking counter so Python never compares the payload objects.",
