    overview:
      "## The core idea\n\nA **trie** (prefix tree) stores a set of strings as a tree of characters. The path from the root to a node spells a prefix; a boolean flag marks where a full word ends. Words that share a prefix share the same path, so `cat`, `car`, and `card` overlap at `ca-`. Lookup and insertion cost **O(L)** in the word length L — independent of how many words are stored — which is the trie's superpower over a hash set for **prefix** work.\n\n## How to think\n\nThe trigger is the word **prefix**: autocomplete, 'words starting with...', 'is any inserted word a prefix of this one', spell-check, IP routing. A hash set answers *exact membership* in O(L) too, but it can't answer *'how many words start with car'* without scanning everything — the trie answers that by walking 5 nodes. Model each node as a dict (or 26-slot array) `children` plus an `is_word` flag. Insertion walks/creates nodes char by char; search walks and checks the flag at the end; `startsWith` walks and just checks you didn't fall off.\n\n## Variants\n\n- **Dict-based node** — `children: {char: node}`, flexible alphabet, easy to write.\n- **Array-based node** — fixed `[26]` slots, faster and cache-friendly for lowercase a-z.\n- **Wildcard search** — on a `.`, recurse into *all* children (LeetCode 211).\n- **Word-grid DFS + trie** — prune board search by checking the trie at each step (Word Search II).\n\n**Edge insight:** the empty string is represented by the root itself carrying `is_word = True`; handle it rather than assuming every word has at least one char.",
